**Explanation:**

The provided Java code defines a REST resource class `MetadataResources` using the RESTEasy framework.  The `@Path` annotation on the class defines the base path `/api/v0/metadata`.  Individual methods are annotated with `@GET` and `@Path` annotations, which define the HTTP method and the specific path for each API endpoint.

The code contains four API endpoints:

1.  `getReleaseVersion`:  Handles requests to `/api/v0/metadata/versions/release`.
2.  `getEndpointStates`: Handles requests to `/api/v0/metadata/endpoints`.
3.  `getLocalDataCenter`: Handles requests to `/api/v0/metadata/localdc`.
4.  `getFeatureSet`: Handles requests to `/api/v0/metadata/versions/features`.

All paths are extracted from string literals within the `@Path` annotations.  The handlers are the methods defined within the `MetadataResources` class.  All entries are for RESTful APIs and are not intended for testing purposes.

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.

handler_in_same_file.description: Whether the handler's implementation is present in the same source code file, rather than being imported.

path_is_prefix.description: Whether the path string is a prefix rather than a full path.

path_from_string_literal.description: Whether the path string is extracted from a literal string defined in the source code.
path_from_string_literal.title: Path From String Literal

path_from_naming_convention.description: Whether the path string is derived from a naming convention supported by the framework.

is_restful_api.description: Whether the API entry is for a RESTful API, rather than other types of APIs.
